	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>OECD review of impact of non-tariff measures and the way forward</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 March 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In January 2013, the OECD published an E-book entitled ‘Non-tariff measures in agri-food trade: Improving policy coherence for development’. The book notes that as classical tariff barriers to trade have been dismantled, so non-tariff measures (NTMs) have taken on greater significance. It points out that NTMs are increasingly being introduced in response to concerns over the environment, food safety, animal welfare and SPS-related matters. It also notes that “most NTMs are put in place to assure that imported products comply with the same standards and regulations as domestic products”, while many are seen as “corrective actions” where markets fail or result in socially inefficient outcomes. As a consequence, it considers that eliminating all NTM-related costs is not feasible.</p><p>The publication identifies three main categories of NTMs:</p>
<ul>

<li>SPS measures; </li>

<li>technical barriers to trade; </li>

<li>other technical measures.</li>

</ul>
<p>According to the OECD analysis, “the trade cost impact of NTMs [is] more important than prevailing tariff rates in obstructing trade”. In addition, private voluntary standards (PVSs) “are often more stringent than public mandatory standards”, becoming “the de facto conditions that determine market access”. PVSs are a particular concern for capital-constrained small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) in developing countries, and can contribute to their exclusion from export market opportunities. For example, in Ghana smallholder pineapple producers consider that there is little point in investing at farm level in meeting PVSs so long as broader infrastructure and service provision is not “upgraded to enable exporters to meet increasingly competitive commercial requirements”.</p><p>In Senegal, case studies have suggested that stricter standards have induced a shift from smallholder-based production to commercial farm-based production for export. It is nevertheless maintained that “financial and technical assistance, as well as continual monitoring, can help smallholders meet the private standards necessary to access [global value chains].”</p><p>Another key observation in the report is that in low-income developing countries where agriculture accounts for a high share of GDP, “food regulation compliance costs have a relatively higher overall economic impact”. It notes that “NTMs may be amongst the reasons why developing countries are not fully utilising market access (tariff) preferences in OECD countries.”</p><p>The analysis calls for more cost–benefit analysis of NTMs. In applying such an approach to cut-flower exports, it found that “the overall effects of tighter inspection are negative.” Specifically it found that:</p>
<ul>

<li>“the increase of inspection costs for the EU outweighs the benefits from reduced infestation for EU producers”; </li>

<li>“tighter inspection leads to losses for foreign suppliers, especially if inspection coincides with depreciated quality due to time spent during inspection”; </li>

<li>improving production methods to reduce inspection requirements also leads “to diminished profits for foreign suppliers”.</li>

</ul>
<p>The analysis argues that “the challenge remains to separate protectionist and non-protectionist measures and to identify measures that are less onerous for trade.” It calls for:</p>
<ul>

<li>better design of development-friendly NTMs;</li>

<li>impact assessments of regulatory changes prior to implementation;</li>

<li>more advanced notice of planned policy changes;</li>

<li>better dialogue and more capacity-building support on standards in developing countries;</li>

<li>the development of national standards consistent with international standards;</li>

<li>greater monitoring of national standards compliance;</li>

<li>greater participation of developing country stakeholders in the design of standards.</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>OECD, ‘Non-tariff measures in agri-food trade: Improving policy coherence for development’, <i>PCD [Policy Coherence for Development] in Focus</i>, 24 January 2013</p><p>
<a href="https://community.oecd.org/docs/DOC-50363  " target="_self">https://community.oecd.org/docs/DOC-50363</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Greater harmonisation of standards applied and verification procedures under various types of NTMs would assist in reducing the costs faced by ACP agri-food product exporters. Ensuring that developing country producers’ needs are increasingly built into basic standards is equally essential. Such changes would enable cost-effective investments to be made in ACP countries in order to meet the standards applied under various NTMs.</p><p>For public standards, improved arbitration mechanisms in cases of dispute would appear to be needed. This applies to both international exports and, increasingly, to intra-regional ACP exports, and would appear essential in order to ensure that the use of NTMs for trade protection purposes is minimised.</p><p>With regard to PVSs, increasing attention needs to be paid to the distribution of costs and benefits along the various supply chains. Currently, the costs of food safety, animal welfare and “greening” measures within the EU are in part borne by the public purse, and there is a growing perception that processors and retailers can secure products which meet stricter standards at little or no additional cost. The expectation of the European retailers is then applied to imports from ACP countries, with the costs of stricter standards being borne largely by primary producers in the ACP.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
